50|$|In the radiosity {{method and}} circuit analogy, several {{assumptions}} {{were made to}} simplify the model. The most significant is that the surface is a diffuse emitter. In such a case, the radiosity {{does not depend on}} the angle of incidence of reflecting radiation and this information is lost on a diffuse surface. In reality, however, the radiosity will have a specular component from the <b>reflected</b> <b>radiation.</b> So, the heat transfer between two surfaces relies on both the view factor and the angle of <b>reflected</b> <b>radiation.</b>|$|E
